{{See also|Lander-Green algorithm}}
The '''Elston&ndash;Stewart algorithm''' is an algorithm for computing the [[likelihood]] of observed genotype data given a [[Pedigree chart|pedigree]].  It is due to [[Robert Elston]] and [[John Stewart (scientist)|John Stewart]].  It can handle relatively large pedigrees providing they are (almost) outbred.  Its computation time is exponential in the number of markers. It is used in the analysis of genetic linkage.

==References==

*Elston, R. C., Stewart, J. (1970) "A new test of association for continuous variables",  ''[[Biometrics (journal)|Biometrics]]'', 26, 305&ndash;314
*Elston, R. C., Stewart, J. (1971) "A general model for the genetic analysis of pedigree data". ''Hum Hered.'', 21, 523&ndash;542
*Mantel, N., Elston, R.C. (1971) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2529015 "Supplements to the Elston-Stewart Test of Association"], ''[[Biometrics (journal)|Biometrics]]'', 27, (2), 460&ndash;462
*Elston R.C., George V.T., Severtson F. (1992) "The Elston-Stewart algorithm for continuous genotypes and environmental factors", ''Hum Hered.'', 42(1), 16&ndash;27.
*Stewart J. (1992) "Genetics and Biology: A Comment on the Significance of the Elston-Stewart Algorithm", ''Hum Hered., 42, 9&ndash;15 {{DOI|10.1159/000154042}}

